          "text": "<teammate-message teammate_id=\"team-lead\">\nYou are implementing Unit 9: Channel binding for identity verification.\n\n## Task\n\nUpdate `build_identity_sign_data()` to include the responder's IP:port in the signed data. This prevents relay attacks where a malicious peer forwards identity challenges to the real peer and replays the response.\n\n## What Needs to Change\n\n### 1. Update `build_identity_sign_data` in `crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs`\n\nCurrent signature (around line 376):\n```rust\npub fn build_identity_sign_data(challenge: &[u8; 32], node_pubkey: &[u8; 32]) -> [u8; 81] {\n    // Layout: \"reme-identity-v1:\" (17) || challenge (32) || node_pubkey (32) = 81 bytes\n```\n\nNew signature — add a `channel` parameter for the responder's socket address:\n```rust\npub fn build_identity_sign_data(\n    challenge: &[u8; 32],\n    node_pubkey: &[u8; 32],\n    channel: Option<&str>,  // e.g. \"192.168.1.50:23003\"\n) -> Vec<u8> {\n    // Layout: \"reme-identity-v2:\" (17) || challenge (32) || node_pubkey (32) || channel_bytes\n    // When channel is None, falls back to v1 layout for backward compatibility\n```\n\nWait — actually, changing the return type from `[u8; 81]` to `Vec<u8>` is a bigger change. Let me reconsider.\n\n**Simpler approach**: Hash the channel binding into the challenge itself, keeping the function signature stable:\n\n```rust\npub fn build_identity_sign_data(\n    challenge: &[u8; 32],\n    node_pubkey: &[u8; 32],\n    channel: Option<&[u8]>,\n) -> [u8; 81] {\n    let bound_challenge = if let Some(channel_bytes) = channel {\n        // Mix channel into challenge: BLAKE3(challenge || channel)\n        let mut hasher = blake3::Hasher::new();\n        hasher.update(challenge);\n        hasher.update(channel_bytes);\n        let hash = hasher.finalize();\n        let mut bound = [0u8; 32];\n        bound.copy_from_slice(&hash.as_bytes()[..32]);\n        bound\n    } else {\n        *challenge\n    };\n\n    let mut sign_data = [0u8; 81];\n    sign_data[..17].copy_from_slice(IDENTITY_SIGN_DOMAIN);\n    sign_data[17..49].copy_from_slice(&bound_challenge);\n    sign_data[49..].copy_from_slice(node_pubkey);\n    sign_data\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Update all callers\n\nSearch for all calls to `build_identity_sign_data` and add `None` as the channel parameter (backward-compatible). Then update the discovery controller to pass the actual channel:\n\n**Callers to update (add `None`):**\n- `apps/node/src/api.rs` — the node's identity endpoint (signs the response)\n- `apps/client/src/tui/http_server.rs` — the client's embedded HTTP server identity endpoint\n- `crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs` — `verify_identity` method\n- `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs` — `verify_peer_identity` method\n- Any tests that call this function\n\n**For the node/client identity endpoints**: They should extract the responder's own bind address and pass it as channel. But since we're adding backward compatibility with `None`, we can pass `None` for now and have the discovery controller pass the actual channel when verifying.\n\nActually, for channel binding to work, BOTH sides must agree on the channel value:\n- The **responder** (node/client endpoint) signs with `channel = Some(own_addr)`\n- The **verifier** (caller) verifies with `channel = Some(responder_addr)`\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Add `channel: Option<&[u8]>` parameter\n2. Update all callers to pass `None` initially (no behavioral change)\n3. The identity endpoint extracts its bind address from the request's `ConnectInfo` and passes it\n4. The verifier passes the URL's host:port\n\nBut step 3 requires Axum `ConnectInfo` extraction which is more complex. For this unit, let's just:\n1. Add the parameter with `None` default\n2. Update all call sites\n3. Add a test proving channel binding works (sign with channel, verify with same channel succeeds, different channel fails)\n\nThe actual wiring of real addresses can happen in Unit 10 (runtime integration).\n\n### 3. Update tests\n\n- Update existing identity endpoint tests to pass `None`\n- Add new tests:\n  - Channel-bound sign + verify with matching channel succeeds\n  - Channel-bound sign + verify with different channel fails\n  - `None` channel matches old behavior (backward compat)\n\n### 4. Exempt node identity endpoint from Basic Auth\n\nThe plan mentions: \"Exempt node identity endpoint from Basic Auth.\" Check if the node's `/api/v1/identity` route is behind Basic Auth middleware. If so, exclude it so unauthenticated LAN peers can verify identity.\n\nCheck `apps/node/src/api.rs` for auth middleware on the identity route.\n\n## Key Files to Modify\n\n- `crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs` — `build_identity_sign_data()` function\n- `apps/node/src/api.rs` — identity endpoint, auth exemption\n- `apps/client/src/tui/http_server.rs` — client identity endpoint\n- `crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs` — `verify_identity` caller\n- `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs` — `verify_peer_identity` caller\n- Test files for all of the above\n\n## Branch Setup\n\n```bash\ngit switch feat/lan-discovery\ngit switch -c feat/channel-binding\n```\n\n## After Implementation\n\n1. Run `cargo test --workspace` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` and `cargo fmt --all -- --check`\n2. Invoke the `simplify` skill to review and clean up your changes\n3. Commit with a clear message\n4. Push and create a PR with `gh pr create --base feat/lan-discovery`\n5. **Wait for CI**: run `gh pr checks <PR_NUMBER>` every 30s, max 15 attempts\n6. **Wait for bot reviews**: run `gh api repos/leon0399/reme/pulls/<PR_NUMBER>/comments --jq 'length'` to check for review comments. Wait until at least Copilot has reviewed (usually 2-5 minutes after push).\n7. If CI fails or reviewers find issues, fix, push, and re-check\n8. Only report DONE when CI is green AND you've read and addressed any bot review comments\n9. Report completion to team lead with PR URL\n</teammate-message>",
